Sorry for the crashes,
Paul

In my area, NW of Atlanta, this app DOES NOT give me a LOCALIZED forecast. It gives me a forecast for a region much further south in the suburban flatlands, not in the mountain foothills. In addition, even though I selected the county airport as my default location, it continues to go back to the southernmost reporting station previously mentioned. This is the biggest negative...this app  DOES NOT GIVE YOU THE LOCALIZED FORCASTS IT PROMISES! Now on a POSITIVE note: the LAYOUT & OPTIONS ARE AWESOME! If/when they get it working properly, it is a FIVE STAR APP FOR SURE*****    ~Response to Developer 3/26/17: I'm speaking about both...to some degree.  The forecasts that your app selects for my location is South of me by about 27 miles and is a relatively flat area in the middle of sprawling suburbia. My location is the foothills of the mountains where temperatures, wind, rainfall, and snow are different than just 27 miles further South. Beyond being more Northerly and in the mountain foothills, we are located at a higher elevation than where your app wants to pull weather forecasts from. For example, over the past few weeks I received forecasts giving low temperatures 4-6 degrees above freezing only to finger the ACTUAL MORNING TEMPERATURES at my home to be as low as 26 degrees. The NWS forecast is typically a pretty accurate forecast, but it needs to be localized to my location. Your app cannot localize it any closer than 23 miles. Like I mentioned, your app keys in on an airport location 27 miles south, or I can get it to focus on an airport West Northwest that is 22 miles away. So, neither the forecasts nor the observations are accurate for my location. I hope this clarifies things for you. I REALLY LIKE what your app is designed to do. Can you possibly access the same data feed as Weather Underground? They have weather reporting stations all around us...like at most schools.*****     ~RESPONSE 2 to Developer: Yes, I can certainly tell the location of the "localized" weather when the app tells me the information is the "current conditions" at McCollum Airport (aka: Cobb County International Airport) in Kennesaw. I'm 4 miles out of Canton.
replyContent: The forecast does NOT come from the airport. The observations may since there is probably an station there, but the predictions come from models based on your location which is unrelated to what station is being used for current observations. This is what I'm trying to explain but I have only 350 characters here. This is why you should email me.

My home screen only gets more tweaked (at one point I had 9 homescreens pages & over 40 widgets, including transparent underlying full-screen Zooper widgets on each page: eventually that setup noticeably slowed down my phone & I had to cut back). Through all the re-arranging, this app's widgets work fine. I do have 2 small complaints: all winter the weather images were over an hour out of sync with actual sunset - and seeing the "daylight" image when it's definitely night out is really depressing. Also, the widget text doesn't scale enough (at all?) so it gets hard to read. But this app has & retains widget space on my main home screen, along with just 2 others (& one of those is Zooper). Great app, thank you!
replyContent: Its difficult to get widgets to work correctly on the normal 4x4 screen config since different devices have different aspect ratios. Try the large widget, it may work better.  -Paul

content: Fairly good weather details and forecasts. Terrible radar. No option for weather or even temperature in status bar. No option for severe weather notifications.

After well over a year, this remains our go-to app even though it's pretty basic. Weather Timeline has nailed down the UI and handiness factor, but NOAA data is awfully reliable and -- like NOAA itself -- the NOAA Weather app breaks down each day's forecast by discrete days and nights: For example, Monday, Monday night, Tuesday, Tuesday night, and so on. Many other apps, including WT, just give midnight-to-midnight forecasts. So, if you want to know what the overnight's going to bring, you need to sort through hourly data for the end of Day 1 and also the beginning of Day 2.  Kudos to the developer, too, for continually nibbling away at issues, such as battery draw when the app first came out. That said, NOAA Weather's nuts-and-bolts UI, and even its bland icon, could use some major creative refreshing and additional handy features.

Make sure you are pinging noaa.gov or open in a web browser from the device.  I've seen networks unable to connect to NOAA while still connecting to other sites.  If the app gets an error, connectivity or otherwise, it then pings a file on my server to verify.  You will get an error report option if the ping succeeds (not connection related).

replyContent:
This isn't a problem with the app.  The restricted network error is an internet connectivity problem.  Some or all of your data is being redirected by the network your connected to.  There are many possible causes.  One example would be if you were connected to a public wifi network and not logged in.  Contact me if you want further help.  

Paul
